> If you love yourself, your body, your titles, your status, your honor, your
> family, your nation etc, your ability to love god will be minimized. If you
> de-focus the mind from all these things and focus it on god, you can love
> god more. Please note than I am not talking about intentionally ignoring or
> mistreating any of these. After all, they too are a small aspect of god.
> But, stop the over-focus of the mind on these things. Do what needs to be
> done to sustain them, but do not focus the mind overly on them.
>
> Whatever you see, think of and do, bring god into it. For example, suppose
> you are taking bath. Think of water as an aspect of god. Be thankful to it
> and pour it on yourself with reverence and a sense of sacredness. Suppose
> you are eating food. Think of food as an aspect of god. Be grateful to it
> and consume it with reverence and a sense of sacredness. Suppose you are
> discussing something with a friend. Think of the friend as an aspect of god
> and deal with him with a sense of sacredness. Suppose you are writing a
> software program on the computer. Think of the computer and the work you do
> as an aspect of god and approach it with reverence and a sense of
> sacredness. This attitude can be extended to every activity.
>
> When you do homam, think that god is indeed in the fire. Be thankful to
> fire and to god. Whatever you offer and chant, do it with feeling. If you
> start identifying god in every perception, thought and action and bring
> awareness of god to every moment of your life, you will realize the infinite
> nature of god and love, devotion and surrender will automatically come.
